ollective future, What Can We Hope For? is filled with striking diagnoses of today’s political crises and creative proposals for solving them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aGlobalizationxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aA. Philip Randolph.  aAchieving Our Country.  aActivism.  aAdvocacy.  aAfterword.  aAgnosticism.  aAllan Bloom.  aAmerican Thinker.  aAnalytic philosophy.  aAnti-authoritarianism.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBetty Friedan.  aCareer.  aCertainty.  aCharles Sanders Peirce.  aCitizenship.  aConscience.  aConservatism.  aConsideration.  aContingency (philosophy).  aCornel West.  aCritique.  aCultural diversity.  aCulture of the United States.  aDocudrama.  aEpithet.  aEthics.  aEthnic cleansing.  aEthos.  aExceptionalism.  aExistence.  aFirst principle.  aGlobal Community.  aGlobal issue.  aGlobalization.  aGreatness.  aGrievance.  aHegemony.  aIdentity politics.  aImagination.  aImperialism.  aIntellectual.  aIrony.  aJane Addams.  aJeremiad.  aJohn Dewey.  aJurisprudence.  aLeft-wing politics.  aLooking Backward.  aMetaphor.  aMetaphysics.  aMoral universalism.  aMorality.  aMotivation.  aMulticulturalism.  aName-dropping.  aNarrative.  aNational security.  aNationalism.  aNovelist.  aPatriotism.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophical Inquiry.  aPhilosophy and the Mirror of Nature.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical correctness.  aPolitics.  aPost-democracy.  aPostmodernism.  aPragmatism.  aPrediction.  aPremise.  aPrinciple.  aPublic sphere.  aRacism.  aRationality.  aRealpolitik.  aReformism.  aRelativism.  aRichard Rorty.  aSelf-concept.  aSelf-criticism.  aSelf-image.  aSocial Gos